04477nam a22005055i 9780226395913DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016014269  a97802263959137 a10.7208/97802263959132doi  a(DE-B1597)549994  a(OCoLC)959884413  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQL542b.M367 2016 4aQL542 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a595.7891 aMarren, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRainbow Dust :bThree Centuries of Butterfly Delight /cPeter Marren. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b18 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. The painted lady -- t1. Meeting the butterfly -- t2. Chasing the clouded yellow -- t3. Graylings the birth of a passion -- t4. Gatekeepers collecting with jean Froissart, john Fowles and Vladimir Nabokov -- t5. Lady glanville’s fritillary -- t6. At the sign of the Chequered skipper -- t7. The golden hog or the wonderful names of butterflies -- t8. Seeing red the admiral -- t9. Fire and brimstone butterflies and the imagination -- t10. Silver washes and pearl borders painting butterflies -- t11. Endgame the large blue and other dropouts -- t12. The wall or how to protect a butterfly -- t13. Envoi aurora or the daughter of dawn -- tAppendix. British butterflies -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLike fluttering shards of stained glass, butterflies possess a unique power to pierce and stir the human soul. Indeed, the ancient Greeks explicitly equated the two in a single word, psyche, so that from early times butterflies were not only a form of life, but also an idea. Profound and deeply personal, written with both wisdom and wit, Peter Marren’s Rainbow Dust explores this idea of butterflies—the why behind the mysterious power of these insects we do not flee, but rather chase. At the age of five, Marren had his “Nabokov Moment,” catching his first butterfly and feeling the dust of its colored scales between his fingers. It was a moment that would launch a lifetime’s fascination rivaling that of the famed novelist—a fascination that put both in good company. From the butterfly collecting and rearing craze that consumed North America and Europe for more than two hundred years (a hobby that in some cases bordered on madness), to the potent allure of butterfly iconography in contemporary advertisements and their use in spearheading calls to conserve and restore habitats (even though butterflies are essentially economically worthless), Marren unveils the many ways in which butterflies inspire us as objects of beauty and as symbols both transient and transcendent. Floating around the globe and through the whole gamut of human thought, from art and literature to religion and science, Rainbow Dust is a cultural history rather than merely a natural one, a tribute to butterflies’ power to surprise, entertain, and obsess us. With a sway that far surpasses their fragile anatomy and gentle beat, butterfly wings draw us into the prismatic wonders of the natural world—and, in the words of Marren, these wonders take flight.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aButterflies. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226395913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226395913.jpg  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles